{{DEFAULTSORT:Jedermann}} [[Category:1961 films]] [[Category:1960s drama films]] [[Category:Austrian drama films]] [[Category:Austrian films]] [[Category:German-language films]] [[Category:Films directed by Gottfried Reinhardt]] [[Category:Austrian films based on plays]] [[Category:Films set in the Middle Ages]] [[Category:Films about death]] [[Category:Personifications of death in fiction]] [[Category:Everyman]] {{Austria-film-stub}}

{{Italic title}} [[File:Jedermann Michelides 52.jpeg|thumb|300px|{{Interlanguage link multi|Cornelius Obonya|de}} and [[Peter Lohmeyer]] portraying ''{{Lang|de|Jedermann}}'' and Death at the [[Salzburg Festival]] in 2014]] '''''{{Lang|de|Jedermann}}''''' (''Everyman'') is a play by the Austrian playwright [[Hugo von Hofmannsthal]]. It is based on several medieval [[mystery play]]s, including the late 15th-century English [[morality play]] ''[[Everyman (play)|Everyman]]''. It was first performed on 1 December 1911 in Berlin under the direction of [[Max Reinhardt]] at the Circus Schumann (which later became the [[Großes Schauspielhaus]]).
''{{Lang|de|Jedermann}}'' has been performed annually at the [[Salzburg Festival]] since 1920,<ref>{{Citation | editor-last = Banham | editor-first = Martin | year = 1998 | title = The Cambridge Guide to Theatre | publisher = Cambridge University Press | page=491.}}</ref> except between 1922 and 1925 and during the years of the [[Anschluss|Nazi annexation of Austria]] and [[World War II]] from 1938 until 1946.<ref>Stevens, Martin. [http://search.proquest.com/openview/706164bbe5cffc126b3c9d7ee512b175/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=1816575 "The Reshaping of ''Everyman'': Hofmannsthal at Salzburg"]. ''Germanic Review'' 48.2 (Mar 1, 1973). p. 117.</ref><ref>[[Salzburg Festival]]: [http://www.salzburgerfestspiele.at/archivdetail/programid/846/id/0/j/1946 ''Jedermann cast of 1946]''. Retrieved November 30, 2016.</ref> Since then, the play has been performed there every year. Amongst the most famous actors performing the title role were [[Curd Jürgens]], [[Klaus Maria Brandauer]], [[Maximilian Schell]] and [[Gert Voss]].
The play has been made into a film at least eight times, including in 1958,<ref>{{IMDb title|0924230|Jedermann|(1958)}}</ref> 1961,<ref>{{IMDb title|0133881|Everyman|(1961)}}</ref> 1970,<ref>{{IMDb title|0417815|Jedermann|(1970)}}</ref> 1983,<ref>{{IMDb title|3036016|Jedermann|(1983)}}</ref> 2000,<ref>{{IMDb title|0293845|Jedermann|(2000)}}</ref> 2004,<ref>{{IMDb title|0460474|Jedermann|(2004)}}</ref> 2010,<ref>{{IMDb title|5179122|Jedermann|(2010)}}</ref> and 2013.<ref>{{IMDb title|3035990|Jedermann|(2013)}}</ref> The 1961 film ''[[Jedermann (film)|Jedermann]]'', directed by Max Reinhardt's son [[Gottfried Reinhardt]] and filmed at the Salzburg Festival, was submitted as the Austrian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[34th Academy Awards]], but it was not selected as one of the five nominees in the category.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences {{Full citation needed|date=July 2016}}</ref>
