{{italic title}} [[Image:Den danske Vitruvius 1 tab003 - Kiöbenhavns Wartegn.jpg|thumb|200px|Depiction in [[Lauritz de Thurah|Thurah]]'s ''[[Den Danske Vitruvius]]'' ]] A '''''Leda and the Swan''''' statue, depicting the classical myth of [[Leda and the Swan]], was from 1611 to 1795 a major [[landmark]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The statue topped a tall column located just off the entrance to the naval [[Christian IV's Arsenal|Arsenal Harbour]].
==History== The monument was built in 1611 during the reign of King [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]]. [[Lauritz de Thurah]]'s ''[[Den Danske Vitruvius]]'' (1st volume, 1746) incorrectly states that the statue was brought home from [[Kalmar]] as [[war loot]].<ref name=Selskabet>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/kko/h/kko_h-6.html|title=Havfruegrunden|publisher=Selskabet for KØbenhavns Historie|accessdate=2011-01-28}}</ref>
The monument was built on an artificial islet with walled sides, on a shallow-watered [[sandbar]] known as the ''Mermaid Bar'' due to a particularly high frequency of reported [[mermaid]] sightings, just outside the entrance to a new naval harbour, the [[Christian IV's Arsenal|Arsenal Harbour]] which was completed about the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/krigshavnen-ved-toejhuset|title=Krigshavnen ved Tøjhuset|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref>
In 1795, the monument was removed when increasing ship traffic in the harbour made it necessary to dig out the area which, by then, was only one metre deep.<ref name=Selskabet/>
The fate of the statue is uncertain. Some reports state that shortly before 1900 it was to be found on a garden lot at [[Frederiksberg Allé]].<ref name=Selskabet/>
